{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Wy4jGqT5v75GF5pm6ZJEHz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So `rabbitmq-2` is running standalone as its own single-node cluster. The fix:\n\n1. **Fix the secret**: Patch `rabbitmq-2` key to `supersecretcookie` (same as `rabbitmq-0` and `rabbitmq-1`)\n2. **Stop `rabbitmq-2`**: Need to stop it so we can reset its Mnesia data (its current Mnesia directory has it running as a standalone cluster with a different cluster ID)\n3. **Reset Mnesia on rabbitmq-2**: Use `rabbitmqctl reset` or `rabbitmqctl force_reset` while the node is stopped\n4. **Join the cluster**: After fixing the secret, I can exec into the pod and use `rabbitmqctl stop_app` to halt the application layer, then `rabbitmqctl reset` to clear Mnesia, followed by `rabbitmqctl join_cluster` to connect it to `rabbitmq-0`, and finally `rabbitmqctl start_app` to bring it back online.\n\nActually, there's a complication—when I exec in, `rabbitmqctl` uses the local cookie (`driftedcookie`), which works for local commands, but `join_cluster` needs to communicate with the target node which has a different cookie, so that would fail. The better approach is to fix the secret first, then delete the pod so it restarts with the correct cookie copied by the initContainer, though the Mnesia database will still have its old standalone state when RabbitMQ starts up and the peer discovery mechanism kicks in.\n\nThe real issue is that RabbitMQ won't do peer discovery on restart if Mnesia data already exists—it just resumes as the same node. So the proper fix requires fixing the secret, restarting the pod, then execing in to run `rabbitmqctl stop_app`, `rabbitmqctl reset` to clear the Mnesia state and make it a blank node, and finally `rabbitmqctl join_cluster` to connect it to the cluster.\n\nAlternatively, I could clear Mnesia while the pod is still running with the wrong cookie (since the local CLI and server share the same cookie), then fix the secret and restart—this way the pod comes back as a blank node and automatically discovers peers. RabbitMQ will rediscover peers automatically after a reset since the Mnesia database gets cleared. So my approach is: patch the secret with the correct cookie, exec into the pod to reset Mnesia, then delete it so it restarts with both the correct cookie and peer discovery enabled.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1532,"cache_read_input_tokens":35448,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1532},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"74bcabbf-73b1-473e-915e-35ec1e2a46c3","uuid":"018b3ed6-8cb6-403f-b946-145172f92b18","request_id":"req_011CcRKthCn6JB3X3d215Bdb"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Wy4jGqT5v75GF5pm6ZJEHz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"`rabbitmq-2` is a standalone single-node cluster with the wrong cookie. The fix requires two steps:\n1. Correct the secret so the initContainer writes the right cookie on restart\n2. Reset `rabbitmq-2`'s Mnesia data and rejoin it to the existing cluster\n\n**Step 1: Fix the Erlang cookie in the secret**"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1532,"cache_read_input_tokens":35448,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1532},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"74bcabbf-73b1-473e-915e-35ec1e2a46c3","uuid":"d08aa92a-1b3e-486c-900f-37236736d57b","request_id":"req_011CcRKthCn6JB3X3d215Bdb"}
