{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VUPWpHajC7A5E42u8oa42u","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The cluster is fully restored. Here's a summary of what was wrong and what was done:\n\n**Root cause:** The `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` Secret had `rabbitmq-2` set to `driftedcookie` while `rabbitmq-0`/`rabbitmq-1` used `supersecretcookie`. RabbitMQ nodes must share an identical Erlang cookie to form a cluster — `rabbitmq-2` booted standalone and formed its own isolated single-node cluster.\n\n**Fix (4 steps, no CRDs/operators):**\n1. **Patched the Secret** — updated `rabbitmq-2`'s key in `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` to `supersecretcookie` (base64: `c3VwZXJzZWNyZXRjb29raWU=`)\n2. **Deleted the pod** — the `copy-cookie` initContainer re-ran and wrote the correct `.erlang.cookie` from the updated Secret\n3. **Reset Mnesia** — `rabbitmqctl stop_app && rabbitmqctl reset` cleared the stale standalone cluster state from `rabbitmq-2`'s PVC\n4. **Rejoined** — `rabbitmqctl join_cluster rabbit@rabbitmq-0...` + `rabbitmqctl start_app` connected it to the existing cluster\n\n**Result:** All 3 disk nodes are Running, no alarms, no network partitions."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1855,"cache_read_input_tokens":40415,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1855},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"74bcabbf-73b1-473e-915e-35ec1e2a46c3","uuid":"09b33fa2-8f4f-4b57-9816-bd8aae56a99d","request_id":"req_011CcRL35jpp3iCmDLqqJCd6"}
